{"title_page": "Alcohol detoxification", "text_new": "[[File:HarmCausedByDrugsTable.svg|thumb|Results of the [[#ISCD|ISCD]] 2010 study ranking the levels of damage caused by drugs, in the opinion of drug-harm experts. When harm to self and others is summed, alcohol was the most harmful of all drugs considered, scoring 72.]]\n\n'''Alcohol detoxification''' (also known as ''detox'') is the abrupt cessation of alcohol intake in individuals that suffer from [[alcohol dependence]]. This process is often coupled with substitution of drugs that have effects similar to the effects of alcohol in order to prevent alcohol withdrawal. When withdrawal does occur, it results in symptoms of varying severity.\n\n==Introduction==\nAs such, the term \"detoxification\" may be somewhat of a misnomer since the process need not refer exclusively to the removal of toxic substances from the body. Detoxification may or may not be indicated depending upon an individual's age, medical status, and history of alcohol intake. For example, a young man who binge drinks and seeks treatment one week after his last use of alcohol may not require detoxification before beginning treatment for alcoholism.\n\n[[Benzodiazepine]]s are the most common family of drugs used for alcohol detoxification,<ref name=\"pmid9214531\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Mayo-Smith MF |title=Pharmacological management of alcohol withdrawal. A meta-analysis and evidence-based practice guideline. American Society of Addiction Medicine Working Group on Pharmacological Management of Alcohol Withdrawal |journal=JAMA |volume=278 |issue=2 |pages=144&ndash;51 |year=1997 |pmid=9214531 |doi=10.1001/jama.278.2.144}} [http://gateway.ovid.com/ovidweb.cgi?T=JS&PAGE=linkout&SEARCH=9214531.ui Full text] at OVID</ref> followed by [[barbiturate]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mohamed |first1=Rashidi |title=Novel pharmacotherapeutic approaches in treatment of alcohol addiction |journal=Scopus |date=2018 |volume=19 |issue=12 |pages=1378\u20134501 |doi=10.2174/1389450119666180523092534 |pmid=29788886 }}</ref>\n\n<br />\n==Symptoms of Withdrawal==\nThe symptoms of alcohol withdrawal can range from mild to severe depending on the level of alcohol dependence a person has experienced. Symptoms can be behavioural (anxiety, agitation, irritability), neurological (tremor, hallucinations), and physical (changes in heart rate, body temperature, blood pressure, nausea and increased risk of seizures). Symptoms typically occur between 6 to 24 hours since cessation of drinking. In severe cases delirium tremens may occur, which is a medical emergency and could result in death. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bayard |first1=Max |title=Alcohol Withdrawal Syndrome |journal=American Family Physician |date=2004 |volume=69 |issue=6 |pages=1443\u201350 |url=https://www.aafp.org/afp/2004/0315/p1443.html|pmid=15053409 }}</ref>\n\n==Benzodiazepines==\n[[Benzodiazepine]]s such as [[chlordiazepoxide]] (Librium), [[diazepam]] (Valium), [[lorazepam]] (Ativan) or [[oxazepam]] (Serax) are the most commonly used drugs used to reduce alcohol withdrawal symptoms.  There are several treatment patterns in which it is used.\n\n# The first option takes into consideration the varying degrees of tolerance. In it, a standard dose of the benzodiazepine is given every half-hour until light sedation is reached. Once a baseline dose is determined, the medication is tapered over the ensuing 3 to 10 days. \n# Another option is to give a standard dose of benzodiazepine based on history and adjust based on withdrawal phenomenon\n# A third option is to defer treatment until symptoms occur. This method should not be used in patients with prior, alcohol-related seizures. This has been effective in [[randomized controlled trials]].<ref name=\"pmid8046805\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Saitz R, Mayo-Smith MF, Roberts MS, Redmond HA, Bernard DR, Calkins DR |title=Individualized treatment for alcohol withdrawal. A randomized double-blind controlled trial |journal=JAMA |volume=272 |issue=7 |pages=519&ndash;23 |year=1994 |pmid=8046805 |doi=10.1001/jama.272.7.519}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid12020181\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Daeppen JB, Gache P, Landry U |title=Symptom-triggered vs fixed-schedule doses of benzodiazepine for alcohol withdrawal: a randomized treatment trial |journal=Arch. Intern. Med. |volume=162 |issue=10 |pages=1117&ndash;21 |year=2002 |pmid=12020181 |doi=10.1001/archinte.162.10.1117|display-authors=etal}}</ref> A non-randomized, before and after, observational study found that symptom triggered therapy was advantageous.<ref name=\"pmid11444401\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Jaeger TM, Lohr RH, Pankratz VS |title=Symptom-triggered therapy for alcohol withdrawal syndrome in medical inpatients |journal=Mayo Clin. Proc. |volume=76 |issue=7 |pages=695&ndash;701 |year=2001 |pmid=11444401 |doi=10.4065/76.7.695}}</ref>\n\nDosing of the benzodiazepines can be guided by the [[Clinical Institute Withdrawal Assessment for Alcohol|CIWA]] scale.<ref name=\"pmid2597811\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Sullivan JT, Sykora K, Schneiderman J, Naranjo CA, Sellers EM |title=Assessment of alcohol withdrawal: the revised clinical institute withdrawal assessment for alcohol scale (CIWA-Ar) |journal=British Journal of Addiction |volume=84 |issue=11 |pages=1353&ndash;7 |year=1989 |pmid=2597811 |doi=10.1111/j.1360-0443.1989.tb00737.x|citeseerx=10.1.1.489.341 }}</ref> The scale is available online.<ref name=\"pmid10102003\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Holbrook AM, Crowther R, Lotter A, Cheng C, King D |title=Diagnosis and management of acute alcohol withdrawal |journal=Canadian Medical Association Journal |volume=160 |issue=5 |pages=675&ndash;80 |year=1999 |pmid=10102003 |doi= |pmc=1230114}} ([http://www.pubmedcentral.nih.gov/articlerender.fcgi?tool=pmcentrez&artid=1230114 see appendix 2])</ref>\n\nRegarding the choice of benzodiazepine:\n* Chlordiazepoxide (Librium) is the benzodiazepine of choice in uncomplicated alcohol withdrawal due to its long half-life.<ref>{{cite web\n|title =Review of the Effectiveness of Treatment for Alcohol Problems\n|author =Duncan Raistrick\n|author2 =Nick Heather\n|author3 =Christine Godfrey\n|last-author-amp =yes\n|date =November 2006\n|work =National Treatment Agency for Substance Misuse, London\n|url =http://www.nta.nhs.uk/uploads/nta_review_of_the_effectiveness_of_treatment_for_alcohol_problems_fullreport_2006_alcohol2.pdf\n|accessdate =2011-11-29\n|archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20111203115017/http://www.nta.nhs.uk/uploads/nta_review_of_the_effectiveness_of_treatment_for_alcohol_problems_fullreport_2006_alcohol2.pdf\n|archive-date =2011-12-03\n|url-status =dead\n}}</ref>\n* Lorazepam or diazepam is available as an injection for patients who cannot safely take medications by mouth.\n* Lorazepam and oxazepam are indicated in patients with impaired liver function because they are metabolised outside of the liver.\n\n==Sympatholytics==\n[[Randomized controlled trials]] have found benefit from [[atenolol]]<ref name=\"pmid2863754\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Kraus ML, Gottlieb LD, Horwitz RI, Anscher M |title=Randomized clinical trial of atenolol in patients with alcohol withdrawal |journal=N. Engl. J. Med. |volume=313 |issue=15 |pages=905&ndash;9 |year=1985 |pmid=2863754 |doi=10.1056/NEJM198510103131501}}</ref> and [[clonidine]].<ref name=\"pmid3300587\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Baumgartner GR, Rowen RC |title=Clonidine vs chlordiazepoxide in the management of acute alcohol withdrawal syndrome |journal=Arch. Intern. Med. |volume=147 |issue=7 |pages=1223&ndash;6 |year=1987 |pmid=3300587 |doi=10.1001/archinte.147.7.1223}}</ref>\n\n==Carbamazepine==\nA [[randomized controlled trial]] has found benefit from [[carbamazepine]].<ref name=\"pmid2653057\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Malcolm R, Ballenger JC, Sturgis ET, Anton R |title=Double-blind controlled trial comparing carbamazepine to oxazepam treatment of alcohol withdrawal |journal=The American Journal of Psychiatry |volume=146 |issue=5 |pages=617&ndash;21 |year=1989 |pmid=2653057 |doi=10.1176/ajp.146.5.617}}</ref>\n\n==Nitrous oxide==\nNitrous oxide has been shown to be an effective and safe treatment for alcohol withdrawal.<ref>Gillman M.A, Lichtigfeld, F.J. 2004 Enlarged double-blind randomised trial of benzodiazepines against psychotropic analgesic nitrous oxide for alcohol withdrawal, ''Addictive Behaviors'', Volume 29, Issue 6, Pages 1183\u20131187</ref> Over 20,000 cases of the alcoholic withdrawal state have been successfully treated with psychotropic analgesic nitrous oxide (PAN) in South Africa and Finland. In 1992 it was officially approved for the treatment of [[addictive]] withdrawal states by the medical authorities in South Africa. Consequently, patients receiving it can claim a refund from their medical insurance. The gas therapy reduces the use of highly addictive sedative medications (like benzopdiazepines and barbiturates) by over 90%. The technique thus reduces the danger of secondary addiction to benzodiazepines, which can be a real problem amongst alcoholics who have been treated with these agents.<ref>[http://www.sabri.org.za/  South African Brain Research Institute]</ref>\n\n==Other drugs==\n[[File:Alcover 17,5 - Gamma-Hydroxybutyric acid.JPG|thumb|GHB sold in Italy for therapeutic use.]]\nSome hospitals administer alcohol to prevent alcohol withdrawal although there are potential problems with this practice.<ref name=\"pmid12578486\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Blondell RD, Dodds HN, Blondell MN |title=Ethanol in formularies of US teaching hospitals |journal=JAMA |volume=289 |issue=5 |pages=552 |year=2003 |pmid=12578486 |doi=10.1001/jama.289.5.552|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\nVarious vitamins, especially from the [[B vitamin|B]] group, are often used during alcohol withdrawal treatment.\n\n[[Sodium oxybate]] is the sodium salt of [[gamma-hydroxybutyric acid]] (GHB).  It is used for both acute alcohol withdrawal and medium to long-term detoxification. This drug enhances GABA neurotransmission and reduces glutamate levels.  It is used in [[Italy]] in small amounts under the trade name [[Alcover]].\n\n[[Baclofen]] has been shown in animal studies and in small human studies to enhance detoxification. This drug acts as a GABA B receptor agonist and this may be beneficial.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Drug detoxification]]\n* [[Detoxification]], the process, real or perceived, of removing toxins from the body.\n*[https://mynaturaldetox.com/ Natural Detox]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{alcohealth}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alcohol Detoxification}}\n[[Category:Alcohol abuse]]\n[[Category:Detoxification]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:HarmCausedByDrugsTable.svg|thumb|Results of the [[#ISCD|ISCD]] 2010 study ranking the levels of damage caused by drugs, in the opinion of drug-harm experts. When harm to self and others is summed, alcohol was the most harmful of all drugs considered, scoring 72.]]\n\n'''Alcohol detoxification''' (also known as ''detox'') is the abrupt cessation of alcohol intake in individuals that suffer from [[alcohol dependence]]. This process is often coupled with substitution of drugs that have effects similar to the effects of alcohol in order to prevent alcohol withdrawal. When withdrawal does occur, it results in symptoms of varying severity.\n\n==Introduction==\nAs such, the term \"detoxification\" may be somewhat of a misnomer since the process need not refer exclusively to the removal of toxic substances from the body. Detoxification may or may not be indicated depending upon an individual's age, medical status, and history of alcohol intake. For example, a young man who binge drinks and seeks treatment one week after his last use of alcohol may not require detoxification before beginning treatment for alcoholism.\n\n[[Benzodiazepine]]s are the most common family of drugs used for alcohol detoxification,<ref name=\"pmid9214531\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Mayo-Smith MF |title=Pharmacological management of alcohol withdrawal. A meta-analysis and evidence-based practice guideline. American Society of Addiction Medicine Working Group on Pharmacological Management of Alcohol Withdrawal |journal=JAMA |volume=278 |issue=2 |pages=144&ndash;51 |year=1997 |pmid=9214531 |doi=10.1001/jama.278.2.144}} [http://gateway.ovid.com/ovidweb.cgi?T=JS&PAGE=linkout&SEARCH=9214531.ui Full text] at OVID</ref> followed by [[barbiturate]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mohamed |first1=Rashidi |title=Novel pharmacotherapeutic approaches in treatment of alcohol addiction |journal=Scopus |date=2018 |volume=19 |issue=12 |pages=1378\u20134501 |doi=10.2174/1389450119666180523092534 |pmid=29788886 }}</ref>\n\n<br />\n==Symptoms of Withdrawal==\nThe symptoms of alcohol withdrawal can range from mild to severe depending on the level of alcohol dependence a person has experienced. Symptoms can be behavioural (anxiety, agitation, irritability), neurological (tremor, hallucinations), and physical (changes in heart rate, body temperature, blood pressure, nausea and increased risk of seizures). Symptoms typically occur between 6 to 24 hours since cessation of drinking. In severe cases delirium tremens may occur, which is a medical emergency and could result in death. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bayard |first1=Max |title=Alcohol Withdrawal Syndrome |journal=American Family Physician |date=2004 |volume=69 |issue=6 |pages=1443\u201350 |url=https://www.aafp.org/afp/2004/0315/p1443.html|pmid=15053409 }}</ref>\n\n==Benzodiazepines==\n[[Benzodiazepine]]s such as [[chlordiazepoxide]] (Librium), [[diazepam]] (Valium), [[lorazepam]] (Ativan) or [[oxazepam]] (Serax) are the most commonly used drugs used to reduce alcohol withdrawal symptoms.  There are several treatment patterns in which it is used.\n\n# The first option takes into consideration the varying degrees of tolerance. In it, a standard dose of the benzodiazepine is given every half-hour until light sedation is reached. Once a baseline dose is determined, the medication is tapered over the ensuing 3 to 10 days. \n# Another option is to give a standard dose of benzodiazepine based on history and adjust based on withdrawal phenomenon\n# A third option is to defer treatment until symptoms occur. This method should not be used in patients with prior, alcohol-related seizures. This has been effective in [[randomized controlled trials]].<ref name=\"pmid8046805\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Saitz R, Mayo-Smith MF, Roberts MS, Redmond HA, Bernard DR, Calkins DR |title=Individualized treatment for alcohol withdrawal. A randomized double-blind controlled trial |journal=JAMA |volume=272 |issue=7 |pages=519&ndash;23 |year=1994 |pmid=8046805 |doi=10.1001/jama.272.7.519}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid12020181\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Daeppen JB, Gache P, Landry U |title=Symptom-triggered vs fixed-schedule doses of benzodiazepine for alcohol withdrawal: a randomized treatment trial |journal=Arch. Intern. Med. |volume=162 |issue=10 |pages=1117&ndash;21 |year=2002 |pmid=12020181 |doi=10.1001/archinte.162.10.1117|display-authors=etal}}</ref> A non-randomized, before and after, observational study found that symptom triggered therapy was advantageous.<ref name=\"pmid11444401\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Jaeger TM, Lohr RH, Pankratz VS |title=Symptom-triggered therapy for alcohol withdrawal syndrome in medical inpatients |journal=Mayo Clin. Proc. |volume=76 |issue=7 |pages=695&ndash;701 |year=2001 |pmid=11444401 |doi=10.4065/76.7.695}}</ref>\n\nDosing of the benzodiazepines can be guided by the [[Clinical Institute Withdrawal Assessment for Alcohol|CIWA]] scale.<ref name=\"pmid2597811\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Sullivan JT, Sykora K, Schneiderman J, Naranjo CA, Sellers EM |title=Assessment of alcohol withdrawal: the revised clinical institute withdrawal assessment for alcohol scale (CIWA-Ar) |journal=British Journal of Addiction |volume=84 |issue=11 |pages=1353&ndash;7 |year=1989 |pmid=2597811 |doi=10.1111/j.1360-0443.1989.tb00737.x|citeseerx=10.1.1.489.341 }}</ref> The scale is available online.<ref name=\"pmid10102003\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Holbrook AM, Crowther R, Lotter A, Cheng C, King D |title=Diagnosis and management of acute alcohol withdrawal |journal=Canadian Medical Association Journal |volume=160 |issue=5 |pages=675&ndash;80 |year=1999 |pmid=10102003 |doi= |pmc=1230114}} ([http://www.pubmedcentral.nih.gov/articlerender.fcgi?tool=pmcentrez&artid=1230114 see appendix 2])</ref>\n\nRegarding the choice of benzodiazepine:\n* Chlordiazepoxide (Librium) is the benzodiazepine of choice in uncomplicated alcohol withdrawal due to its long half-life.<ref>{{cite web\n|title =Review of the Effectiveness of Treatment for Alcohol Problems\n|author =Duncan Raistrick\n|author2 =Nick Heather\n|author3 =Christine Godfrey\n|last-author-amp =yes\n|date =November 2006\n|work =National Treatment Agency for Substance Misuse, London\n|url =http://www.nta.nhs.uk/uploads/nta_review_of_the_effectiveness_of_treatment_for_alcohol_problems_fullreport_2006_alcohol2.pdf\n|accessdate =2011-11-29\n|archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20111203115017/http://www.nta.nhs.uk/uploads/nta_review_of_the_effectiveness_of_treatment_for_alcohol_problems_fullreport_2006_alcohol2.pdf\n|archive-date =2011-12-03\n|url-status =dead\n}}</ref>\n* Lorazepam or diazepam is available as an injection for patients who cannot safely take medications by mouth.\n* Lorazepam and oxazepam are indicated in patients with impaired liver function because they are metabolised outside of the liver.\n\n==Sympatholytics==\n[[Randomized controlled trials]] have found benefit from [[atenolol]]<ref name=\"pmid2863754\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Kraus ML, Gottlieb LD, Horwitz RI, Anscher M |title=Randomized clinical trial of atenolol in patients with alcohol withdrawal |journal=N. Engl. J. Med. |volume=313 |issue=15 |pages=905&ndash;9 |year=1985 |pmid=2863754 |doi=10.1056/NEJM198510103131501}}</ref> and [[clonidine]].<ref name=\"pmid3300587\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Baumgartner GR, Rowen RC |title=Clonidine vs chlordiazepoxide in the management of acute alcohol withdrawal syndrome |journal=Arch. Intern. Med. |volume=147 |issue=7 |pages=1223&ndash;6 |year=1987 |pmid=3300587 |doi=10.1001/archinte.147.7.1223}}</ref>\n\n==Carbamazepine==\nA [[randomized controlled trial]] has found benefit from [[carbamazepine]].<ref name=\"pmid2653057\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Malcolm R, Ballenger JC, Sturgis ET, Anton R |title=Double-blind controlled trial comparing carbamazepine to oxazepam treatment of alcohol withdrawal |journal=The American Journal of Psychiatry |volume=146 |issue=5 |pages=617&ndash;21 |year=1989 |pmid=2653057 |doi=10.1176/ajp.146.5.617}}</ref>\n\n==Nitrous oxide==\nNitrous oxide has been shown to be an effective and safe treatment for alcohol withdrawal.<ref>Gillman M.A, Lichtigfeld, F.J. 2004 Enlarged double-blind randomised trial of benzodiazepines against psychotropic analgesic nitrous oxide for alcohol withdrawal, ''Addictive Behaviors'', Volume 29, Issue 6, Pages 1183\u20131187</ref> Over 20,000 cases of the alcoholic withdrawal state have been successfully treated with psychotropic analgesic nitrous oxide (PAN) in South Africa and Finland. In 1992 it was officially approved for the treatment of [[addictive]] withdrawal states by the medical authorities in South Africa. Consequently, patients receiving it can claim a refund from their medical insurance. The gas therapy reduces the use of highly addictive sedative medications (like benzopdiazepines and barbiturates) by over 90%. The technique thus reduces the danger of secondary addiction to benzodiazepines, which can be a real problem amongst alcoholics who have been treated with these agents.<ref>[http://www.sabri.org.za/  South African Brain Research Institute]</ref>\n\n==Other drugs==\n[[File:Alcover 17,5 - Gamma-Hydroxybutyric acid.JPG|thumb|GHB sold in Italy for therapeutic use.]]\nSome hospitals administer alcohol to prevent alcohol withdrawal although there are potential problems with this practice.<ref name=\"pmid12578486\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Blondell RD, Dodds HN, Blondell MN |title=Ethanol in formularies of US teaching hospitals |journal=JAMA |volume=289 |issue=5 |pages=552 |year=2003 |pmid=12578486 |doi=10.1001/jama.289.5.552|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\nVarious vitamins, especially from the [[B vitamin|B]] group, are often used during alcohol withdrawal treatment.\n\n[[Sodium oxybate]] is the sodium salt of [[gamma-hydroxybutyric acid]] (GHB).  It is used for both acute alcohol withdrawal and medium to long-term detoxification. This drug enhances GABA neurotransmission and reduces glutamate levels.  It is used in [[Italy]] in small amounts under the trade name [[Alcover]].\n\n[[Baclofen]] has been shown in animal studies and in small human studies to enhance detoxification. This drug acts as a GABA B receptor agonist and this may be beneficial.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Drug detoxification]]\n* [[Detoxification]], the process, real or perceived, of removing toxins from the body.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{alcohealth}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alcohol Detoxification}}\n[[Category:Alcohol abuse]]\n[[Category:Detoxification]]\n", "name_user": "Ashishjain3221", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSee also)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_detoxification"}
{"title_page": "Shaquill Griffin", "text_new": "{{short description|American football cornerback}}\n{{redirect|Shaq Griffin|his brother, the linebacker|Shaquem Griffin}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Shaquill Griffin\n| image               = Shaquill Griffin.JPG\n| image_size          = 225px\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Griffin with the Seattle Seahawks in 2018\n| current_team        = Seattle Seahawks\n| number              = 26\n| position            = [[Cornerback]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1995|7|20}}\n| birth_place         = [[St. Petersburg, Florida]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 0\n| weight_lbs          = 194\n| high_school         = [[Lakewood High School (Florida)|Lakewood]]<br>([[St. Petersburg, Florida]])\n| college             = [[UCF Knights football|UCF]]\n| draftyear           = 2017\n| draftround          = 3\n| draftpick           = 90\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Seattle Seahawks]] ({{NFL Year|2017}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Active\n| highlights          =* [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2020 Pro Bowl|2019]]) \n* Second-team All-AAC (2016)\n|statweek=13\n|statseason=2019\n|statlabel1=[[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]]\n|statvalue1=173\n|statlabel2=[[Quarterback sacks|Sacks]] \n|statvalue2=1.0\n|statlabel3=[[Fumble|Forced fumbles]] \n|statvalue3=0\n|statlabel4=[[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n|statvalue4=0\n|statlabel5=[[Pass deflections]] \n|statvalue5=36\n|statlabel6=[[Interceptions]] \n|statvalue6=3\n| nflnew              = shaquillgriffin/2558259\n| pfr                 =\n}}\n\n'''Shaquill Griffin''' {{IPAc-en|\u0283|\u0259|\u02c8|k|i\u02d0|l}} (born July 20, 1995) is an [[American football]] [[cornerback]] for the [[Seattle Seahawks]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He is the twin brother of fellow Seahawks player [[Shaquem Griffin]],<ref name=\"Shaquem drafted\">{{cite web|last1=|first1=|title=One-handed LB Shaquem Griffin drafted by Seahawks, reunited with twin brother Shaquill|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/draft2018/story/_/id/23347129/one-handed-lb-shaquem-griffin-drafted-seattle-seahawks-reunited-twin-brother-shaquill|website=[[ESPN.com]]|date=April 28, 2018}}</ref> and both brothers played [[college football]] for the [[UCF Knights football|University of Central Florida Knights]].<ref>{{cite web|title=For UCF standout Shaquill Griffin, NFL dream is all about family|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/ucf-knights/knights-notepad/os-sp-ucf-shaquill-griffin-nfl-draft-0425-story.html|last=Green|first=Shannon|website=OrlandoSentinel.com|date=April 24, 2017|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nShaquill Griffin was born to Tangie and Terry Griffin<ref name=\"ESPN-Early\">{{cite news|last1=Glock|first1=Allison|title=NCF: Identical twins have NFL dreams, with only three hands|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/page/bodyissue2013griffins/central-florida-shaquill-shaquem-griffin-three-hands-nfl-dreams-espn-magazine|work=ESPN.com}}</ref> on July 20, 1995, less than two minutes before [[Shaquem Griffin|Shaquem]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Drahold|first1=Bryon|title=Seahawks cornerback Shaquill Griffin kept promise to twin brother|url=http://seahawkswire.usatoday.com/2017/05/02/seahawks-cornerback-shaquill-griffin-keeps-promise-to-twin-bother/|website=Seahawks Wire|date=May 2, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"SI-Unstoppable\">{{cite news|last1=Staples|first1=Andy|title=Shaquem Griffin: UCF's unstoppable one-handed star|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2017/11/16/shaquem-griffin-hand-ucf-nfl-draft|work=Sports Illustrated|date=November 16, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Shaquill and Shaquem competed together in track, baseball, and football. At age 4 Griffin had his left hand amputated due to [[constriction ring syndrome]].<ref name=\"ESPN-Early\" />\n\n==High school career==\nGriffin attended [[Lakewood High School (Florida)|Lakewood High School]] in [[St. Petersburg, Florida]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/sports/lakewoods-shaquill-griffin-hopes-to-give-back-after-realizing-nfl-dream/436232655 |title=Lakewood's Shaquill Griffin hopes to give back after realizing NFL dream |work=10NEWS |access-date=October 5, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> He played [[high school football]] for the Spartans. He chose to attend UCF after high school.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ucfknights.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=277 |title=Shaquill Griffin |website=ucfknights.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nGriffin played for the [[UCF Knights football|University of Central Florida (UCF) Knights]] from 2013 to 2016,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/shaquill-griffin-1.html |title=Shaquill Griffin College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> rejecting offers from other teams including the [[Miami Hurricanes]], his dream team, to play with his twin brother [[Shaquem Griffin|Shaquem]].<ref name=\"Orr\" /> He left UCF one season before Shaquem, as Shaquem [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirted]] his freshman year while Shaquill saw playing time.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Knight|first1=Joey|title=Griffin twins go their separate ways on the gridiron for first time|url=http://www.tampabay.com/sports/college/griffin-twins-go-their-separate-ways-on-the-gridiron-for-first-time/2332417|work=Tampa Bay Times|date=August 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=2013 Football Roster: Shaquem Griffin Bio|url=http://ucfknights.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=577|work=UCFKnights.com|date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=2013 Football Roster: Shaquill Griffin Bio|url=http://ucfknights.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=277|work=UCFKnights.com|date=}}</ref>\n\nAs a freshman, Shaquill recorded six total tackles and one pass defensed in four games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/shaquill-griffin-1/gamelog/2013/ |title=Shaquill Griffin 2013 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> As a sophomore, Shaquill recorded 15 total tackles and an interception in six games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/shaquill-griffin-1/gamelog/2014/ |title=Shaquill Griffin 2014 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> As a junior, he recorded 43 total tackles, one interception returned for a touchdown (against Temple), and 11 passes defensed in 11 games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-10-17-temple.html |title=UCF at Temple Box Score, October 17, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/shaquill-griffin-1/gamelog/2015 |title=Shaquill Griffin 2015 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> As a senior, he recorded 49 total tackles, four interceptions (one against Tulane returned for a touchdown), 15 passes defensed, and one fumble recovery.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2016-11-05-central-florida.html |title=Tulane at Central Florida Box Score, November 5, 2016 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/shaquill-griffin-1/gamelog/2016 |title=Shaquill Griffin 2016 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year \n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team \n! rowspan=\"2\"| GP \n! colspan=\"4\"| Tackles\n! colspan=\"5\"| Interceptions\n|-\n! Comb !! Total !! Ast !! Sack !! Int !! Yards !! Avg !! TD !! PD \n|-\n! [[2013 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2013]] !! [[2013 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]\n| 4 || 6 || 5 || 1 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 1\n|-\n! [[2014 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2014]] !! [[2014 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]\n| 6 || 15 || 1 || 4 || 0.0 || 1 || 20 || 20.0 || 0 || 0 \n|-\n! [[2015 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2015]] !! [[2015 UCF Knights football team|UCF]] \n| 11 || 43 || 33 || 10 || 0.0 || 1 || 102 || 102.0 || 1 || 11\n|-\n! [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2016]] !! [[2016 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]\n| 13 || 49 || 30 || 19 || 0.0 || 4 || 46 || 11.5 || 1 || 15\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career !! 34 !! 113 !! 79 !! 34 !! 0.0 !! 6 !! 168 !! 28.0 !! 2 !! 27\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nOn October 4, 2017, it was announced that Griffin had accepted his invitation to the [[NFLPA Collegiate Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web| title=35 Collegiate Bowl Players Invited to 2017 NFL Combine| url=http://collegiate.nflpa.com/2017/10/04/35-collegiate-bowl-players-invited-to-2017-nfl-combine/| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=Collegiate.NFLPA.com}}</ref> On January 24, 2017, he appeared in the NFLPA Collegiate Bowl for [[Jim Zorn]]'s American team and recorded three combined tackles as they lost 27\u20137 to the National team.<ref>{{cite web| title=2017 NFLPA COLLEGIATE BOWL \u2013 FINAL STATS| url=http://www.tonysoftli.com/nfl/2017-nflpa-collegiate-bowl-final-stats/| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=TonySoftli.com| first=Tony|last=Softli| date=January 28, 2017}}</ref> He was one of 35 collegiate cornerbacks to be invited to the [[NFL Scouting Combine]] in [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]].<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Combine 2017: Complete list of invited players| url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2017/02/nfl_combine_2017_complete_list.html| accessdate=January 23, 2018| website=Cleveland.com| first=Scott |last=Patsko| date=February 27, 2017}}</ref> Griffin was a top performer among his position group, finishing second in the broad jump, third in the vertical jump, and ran the fourth-fastest [[40-yard dash]] among all defensive backs. On March 22, 2017, Griffin attended Central Florida's pro day, but opted to stand on his combine numbers and only performed positional drills for team representatives and scouts from 20 [[National Football League|NFL]] teams and three [[Canadian Football League|CFL]] teams. Throughout the draft process, Griffin had private workouts and visits with multiple teams, including the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]], [[Tennessee Titans]], [[Detroit Lions]], [[Indianapolis Colts]], [[San Francisco 49ers]], [[Seattle Seahawks]], [[Dallas Cowboys]], and [[Philadelphia Eagles]].<ref name=\"Orr\">{{cite web| title=Shaquill Griffin stuck by his twin; now NFL teams are catching up| url=https://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000794221/article/shaquill-griffin-stuck-by-his-twin-now-nfl-teams-are-catching-up|last=Orr|first=Conor| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Draft 2017: Athletic cornerback Shaquill Griffin visits Eagles| url=https://www.bleedinggreennation.com/platform/amp/2017/4/19/15365722/nfl-draft-2017-shaquill-griffin-eagles-visits-cornerback-athletic-ucf-central-florida-philadelphia| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=bleedinggreennation.com| first=Brandon Lee |last=Gowton| date=April 19, 2017}}</ref> At the conclusion of the pre-draft process, Griffin was projected to be a third- or fourth-round pick by NFL draft experts and scouts. He was ranked the 17th-best cornerback prospect in the draft by NFLDraftScout.com.<ref>{{cite web| title=Shaquill Griffin, DS #17 CB, Central Florida| url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=127195&draftyear=2017&genpos=CB| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=nfldraftscout.com}}</ref>\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 0\u215b\n|       weight = 194\n|         dash = 4.38\n|    ten split = 1.52\n| twenty split = 2.55\n|      shuttle = 4.14\n|   cone drill = 6.87\n|     vertical = 38\u00bd\n|     broad ft = 11\n|     broad in = 0\n|        bench = 17\n|    wonderlic = \n|     arm span = 32\u215c\n|    hand span = 8\u00be\n|         note = All values from [[NFL Combine]]<ref>{{cite web |title= NFL Draft Profile: Shaquill Griffin |url= http://www.nfl.com/draft/2017/profiles/shaquill-griffin?id=2558259 |accessdate= January 2, 2018 |website= NFL.com}}</ref><ref>http://www.draftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=127195&draftyear=2017&genpos=CB</ref>\n}}\nThe [[Seattle Seahawks]] selected Griffin in the third round (90th overall) of the [[2017 NFL Draft]]. He was the 13th cornerback selected in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seattle Seahawks Select Central Florida Cornerback Shaquill Griffin With No. 90 Overall Pick In 2017 NFL Draft|url=http://www.seahawks.com/news/2017/04/28/seattle-seahawks-select-central-florida-cornerback-shaquill-griffin-no-90-overall|author=Yohannes, Aron|website=Seahawks.com|date=April 28, 2017|accessdate=May 11, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503073103/http://www.seahawks.com/news/2017/04/28/seattle-seahawks-select-central-florida-cornerback-shaquill-griffin-no-90-overall|archivedate=May 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2017/draft.htm |title=2017 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nOn June 15, 2017, the Seattle Seahawks signed Griffin to a four-year, [[United States dollar|$]]3.25 million [[contract]] that includes a [[signing bonus]] of $758,620.<ref>{{cite web| title=Spotrac.com: Shaquill Griffin| url=http://www.spotrac.com/nfl/seattle-seahawks/shaquill-griffin-21832/| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=Spotrac.com}}</ref> Griffin joined the defensive unit nicknamed the [[Legion of Boom (Seattle Seahawks)|Legion of Boom]] for its final season.\n\nThroughout training camp, Griffin competed against [[Jeremy Lane]], [[DeShawn Shead]], and [[Neiko Thorpe]] for the starting cornerback job. Head coach [[Pete Carroll]] named Griffin the fourth cornerback on the depth chart behind [[Richard Sherman (American football)|Richard Sherman]], Jeremy Lane, and Neiko Thorpe.<ref>{{cite web| title=Seahawks depth chart following 53-man cutdown| url=https://www.fieldgulls.com/platform/amp/2017/9/3/16249288/seahawks-depth-chart-following-53-man-cutdown| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=FieldGulls.com| first=Kenneth |last=Arthur| date=September 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe made his professional regular season debut in the [[2017 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]]' season-opener at the [[2017 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]] and made a season-high ten combined tackles and deflected one pass during their 17\u20139 loss. Griffin played the majority of the game after Jeremy Lane was ejected in the first quarter after allegedly throwing a punch at Packers wide receiver [[Davante Adams]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709100gnb.htm|title=Seattle Seahawks at Green Bay Packers - September 10th, 2017|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref> On October 8, 2017, Griffin made his first career start after Jeremy Lane was inactive after suffering a [[groin]] injury during their Week 4 victory over the [[2017 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Seahawks lose Chris Carson, Jeremy Lane, Cliff Avril to injuries; Rees Odhiambo taken to hospital| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/20890152/seattle-seahawks-lose-jeremy-lane-cliff-avril-injuries-vs-indianapolis-colts| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=ESPN.com| first=Brady |last=Henderson| date=October 2, 2017}}</ref> He finished the Seahawks' 16\u201310 win against the [[2017 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]] with six solo tackles and one pass deflection.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201710080ram.htm |title=Seattle Seahawks at Los Angeles Rams - October 8th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> The following week, Griffin earned his second consecutive start with Lane still inactive and recorded three solo tackles and a season-high three pass deflections in Seattle's 24\u20137 victory at the [[2017 New York Giants season|New York Giants]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201710220nyg.htm |title=Seattle Seahawks at New York Giants - October 22nd, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> After Lane returned from injury, head coach [[Pete Carroll]] stated Griffin would remain the starting cornerback entering Week 8.<ref>{{cite web| title=Jeremy Lane benched for Shaquill Griffin in latest example of Seahawks\u2019 \u2018Always Compete\u2019 philosophy| url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/seahawks/seahawks-coach-pete-carroll-says-benching-of-jeremy-lane-reveals-that-seahawks-truly-always-compete/| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=SeattleTimes.com| first=Bob |last=Condotta| date=October 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn November 20, 2017, Griffin recorded one solo tackle before leaving the Seahawks' 34\u201331 loss to the [[2017 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] in the first quarter after suffering a [[concussion]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Seahawks CB Shaquill Griffin leaves Monday night game against Falcons with concussion| url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/seahawks/seattle-seahawks-atlanta-falcons-shaquill-griffin-doubtful-to-return-concussion/| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=SeattleTimes.com| first=Evan |last=Webeck| date=November 20, 2017}}</ref> He remained in concussion protocol and was inactive for the Seahawks' 24\u201313 victory at the [[2017 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]] in Week 12. During a Week 16 matchup at the [[2017 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]], Griffin collected five combined tackles and made his first career sack on [[Dak Prescott]] as the Seahawks defeated them 21\u201312.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712240dal.htm |title=Seattle Seahawks at Dallas Cowboys - December 24th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> On December 31, 2017, Griffin recorded six solo tackles, deflected two passes, and made his first career interception during their 26\u201324 loss to the [[2017 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]]. His first career interception came in the third quarter off a pass attempt by [[Drew Stanton]] intended for [[Jaron Brown]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712310sea.htm |title=Arizona Cardinals at Seattle Seahawks - December 31st, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Game Center: Week 17-2017: Arizona Cardinals @ Seattle Seahawks| url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2017123115/2017/REG17/cardinals@seahawks| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> He finished the {{NFL Year|2017}} season with 59 combined tackles (50 solo), 15 pass deflections, one interception, and one sack in 15 games and 11 starts.<ref>{{cite web |title= NFL Player stats: Shaquill Griffin (Career) |url= http://www.nfl.com/player/shaquillgriffin/2558259/careerstats |accessdate= January 2, 2018 |website= NFL.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GrifSh00/gamelog/2017/ |title=Shaquill Griffin 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> [[Pro Football Focus]] gave Griffin an overall grade of 77.2, ranking as the 58th-highest grade among all qualified cornerbacks in 2017.<ref>{{cite web| title=Pro Football Focus: Shaquille Griffin| url=https://www.profootballfocus.com/nfl/players/shaquill-griffin/11845| accessdate=April 20, 2018| website=profootballfocus.com}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nGriffin was reunited with his twin brother Shaquem in the 2018 season, as Shaquem was drafted by the Seahawks in the fifth round (141st overall) of the [[2018 NFL Draft]] on April 28, 2018.<ref name=\"Shaquem drafted\" />\n\nOn September 17, 2018, Griffin notched two interceptions and three pass deflections against [[2018 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]] quarterback [[Mitchell Trubisky]] in a 17-24 road loss at [[Soldier Field]].\n<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/seahawks/seahawks-cb-shaquill-griffin-still-learning-from-his-big-brother-richard-sherman/ |title=Seahawks CB Shaquill Griffin still learning from his \u2018big brother,\u2019 Richard Sherman |last=Vorel |first=Mike |date=September 21, 2018 |work=The Seattle Times |access-date=October 5, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nGriffin was named to the [[Pro Bowl]] on January 17, 2020 as an alternate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seahawks.com/news/thursday-round-up-seattle-seahawks-coaching-staff-selected-to-lead-nfc-team-at-2?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook|title=Thursday Round-Up: Seattle Seahawks Coaching Staff Selected To Lead NFC Team At 2020 Pro Bowl|website=www.seahawks.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://ucfknights.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=277 UCF Knights bio]\n*[https://www.seahawks.com/team/players-roster/shaquill-griffin/ Seattle Seahawks bio]\n*{{ESPN NFL}}\n*{{NFL player|2558259}}\n*{{Footballstats |pfr=GrifSh00}}\n\n{{Seahawks2017DraftPicks}}\n{{Seattle Seahawks roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Griffin, Shaquill}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:American football cornerbacks]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Florida]]\n[[Category:Seattle Seahawks players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from St. Petersburg, Florida]]\n[[Category:Twin people from the United States]]\n[[Category:Twin sportspeople]]\n[[Category:UCF Knights football players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football cornerback}}\n{{redirect|Shaq Griffin|his brother, the linebacker|Shaquem Griffin}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Shaquill Griffin\n| image               = Shaquill Griffin.JPG\n| image_size          = 225px\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Griffin with the Seattle Seahawks in 2018\n| current_team        = Seattle Seahawks\n| number              = 26\n| position            = [[Cornerback]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1995|7|20}}\n| birth_place         = [[St. Petersburg, Florida]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 0\n| weight_lbs          = 194\n| high_school         = [[Lakewood High School (Florida)|Lakewood]]<br>([[St. Petersburg, Florida]])\n| college             = [[UCF Knights football|UCF]]\n| draftyear           = 2017\n| draftround          = 3\n| draftpick           = 90\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Seattle Seahawks]] ({{NFL Year|2017}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Active\n| highlights          =* [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2020 Pro Bowl|2019]]) \n* Second-team All-AAC (2016)\n|statweek=13\n|statseason=2019\n|statlabel1=[[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]]\n|statvalue1=173\n|statlabel2=[[Quarterback sacks|Sacks]] \n|statvalue2=1.0\n|statlabel3=[[Fumble|Forced fumbles]] \n|statvalue3=0\n|statlabel4=[[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n|statvalue4=0\n|statlabel5=[[Pass deflections]] \n|statvalue5=36\n|statlabel6=[[Interceptions]] \n|statvalue6=3\n| nflnew              = shaquillgriffin/2558259\n| pfr                 =\n}}\n\n'''Shaquill Griffin''' {{IPAc-en|\u0283|\u0259|\u02c8|k|i\u02d0|l}} (born July 20, 1995) is an [[American football]] [[cornerback]] for the [[Seattle Seahawks]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He is the twin brother of fellow Seahawks player [[Shaquem Griffin]],<ref name=\"Shaquem drafted\">{{cite web|last1=|first1=|title=One-handed LB Shaquem Griffin drafted by Seahawks, reunited with twin brother Shaquill|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/draft2018/story/_/id/23347129/one-handed-lb-shaquem-griffin-drafted-seattle-seahawks-reunited-twin-brother-shaquill|website=[[ESPN.com]]|date=April 28, 2018}}</ref> and both brothers played [[college football]] for the [[UCF Knights football|University of Central Florida Knights]].<ref>{{cite web|title=For UCF standout Shaquill Griffin, NFL dream is all about family|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/ucf-knights/knights-notepad/os-sp-ucf-shaquill-griffin-nfl-draft-0425-story.html|last=Green|first=Shannon|website=OrlandoSentinel.com|date=April 24, 2017|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nShaquill Griffin was born to Tangie and Terry Griffin<ref name=\"ESPN-Early\">{{cite news|last1=Glock|first1=Allison|title=NCF: Identical twins have NFL dreams, with only three hands|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/page/bodyissue2013griffins/central-florida-shaquill-shaquem-griffin-three-hands-nfl-dreams-espn-magazine|work=ESPN.com}}</ref> on July 20, 1995, less than two minutes before [[Shaquem Griffin|Shaquem]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Drahold|first1=Bryon|title=Seahawks cornerback Shaquill Griffin kept promise to twin brother|url=http://seahawkswire.usatoday.com/2017/05/02/seahawks-cornerback-shaquill-griffin-keeps-promise-to-twin-bother/|website=Seahawks Wire|date=May 2, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"SI-Unstoppable\">{{cite news|last1=Staples|first1=Andy|title=Shaquem Griffin: UCF's unstoppable one-handed star|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2017/11/16/shaquem-griffin-hand-ucf-nfl-draft|work=Sports Illustrated|date=November 16, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Shaquill and Shaquem competed together in track, baseball, and football.<ref name=\"ESPN-Early\" />\n\n==High school career==\nGriffin attended [[Lakewood High School (Florida)|Lakewood High School]] in [[St. Petersburg, Florida]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/sports/lakewoods-shaquill-griffin-hopes-to-give-back-after-realizing-nfl-dream/436232655 |title=Lakewood's Shaquill Griffin hopes to give back after realizing NFL dream |work=10NEWS |access-date=October 5, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> He played [[high school football]] for the Spartans. He chose to attend UCF after high school.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ucfknights.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=277 |title=Shaquill Griffin |website=ucfknights.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nGriffin played for the [[UCF Knights football|University of Central Florida (UCF) Knights]] from 2013 to 2016,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/shaquill-griffin-1.html |title=Shaquill Griffin College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> rejecting offers from other teams including the [[Miami Hurricanes]], his dream team, to play with his twin brother [[Shaquem Griffin|Shaquem]].<ref name=\"Orr\" /> He left UCF one season before Shaquem, as Shaquem [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirted]] his freshman year while Shaquill saw playing time.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Knight|first1=Joey|title=Griffin twins go their separate ways on the gridiron for first time|url=http://www.tampabay.com/sports/college/griffin-twins-go-their-separate-ways-on-the-gridiron-for-first-time/2332417|work=Tampa Bay Times|date=August 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=2013 Football Roster: Shaquem Griffin Bio|url=http://ucfknights.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=577|work=UCFKnights.com|date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=2013 Football Roster: Shaquill Griffin Bio|url=http://ucfknights.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=277|work=UCFKnights.com|date=}}</ref>\n\nAs a freshman, Shaquill recorded six total tackles and one pass defensed in four games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/shaquill-griffin-1/gamelog/2013/ |title=Shaquill Griffin 2013 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> As a sophomore, Shaquill recorded 15 total tackles and an interception in six games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/shaquill-griffin-1/gamelog/2014/ |title=Shaquill Griffin 2014 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> As a junior, he recorded 43 total tackles, one interception returned for a touchdown (against Temple), and 11 passes defensed in 11 games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-10-17-temple.html |title=UCF at Temple Box Score, October 17, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/shaquill-griffin-1/gamelog/2015 |title=Shaquill Griffin 2015 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> As a senior, he recorded 49 total tackles, four interceptions (one against Tulane returned for a touchdown), 15 passes defensed, and one fumble recovery.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2016-11-05-central-florida.html |title=Tulane at Central Florida Box Score, November 5, 2016 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/shaquill-griffin-1/gamelog/2016 |title=Shaquill Griffin 2016 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year \n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team \n! rowspan=\"2\"| GP \n! colspan=\"4\"| Tackles\n! colspan=\"5\"| Interceptions\n|-\n! Comb !! Total !! Ast !! Sack !! Int !! Yards !! Avg !! TD !! PD \n|-\n! [[2013 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2013]] !! [[2013 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]\n| 4 || 6 || 5 || 1 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 1\n|-\n! [[2014 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2014]] !! [[2014 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]\n| 6 || 15 || 1 || 4 || 0.0 || 1 || 20 || 20.0 || 0 || 0 \n|-\n! [[2015 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2015]] !! [[2015 UCF Knights football team|UCF]] \n| 11 || 43 || 33 || 10 || 0.0 || 1 || 102 || 102.0 || 1 || 11\n|-\n! [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2016]] !! [[2016 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]\n| 13 || 49 || 30 || 19 || 0.0 || 4 || 46 || 11.5 || 1 || 15\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career !! 34 !! 113 !! 79 !! 34 !! 0.0 !! 6 !! 168 !! 28.0 !! 2 !! 27\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nOn October 4, 2017, it was announced that Griffin had accepted his invitation to the [[NFLPA Collegiate Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web| title=35 Collegiate Bowl Players Invited to 2017 NFL Combine| url=http://collegiate.nflpa.com/2017/10/04/35-collegiate-bowl-players-invited-to-2017-nfl-combine/| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=Collegiate.NFLPA.com}}</ref> On January 24, 2017, he appeared in the NFLPA Collegiate Bowl for [[Jim Zorn]]'s American team and recorded three combined tackles as they lost 27\u20137 to the National team.<ref>{{cite web| title=2017 NFLPA COLLEGIATE BOWL \u2013 FINAL STATS| url=http://www.tonysoftli.com/nfl/2017-nflpa-collegiate-bowl-final-stats/| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=TonySoftli.com| first=Tony|last=Softli| date=January 28, 2017}}</ref> He was one of 35 collegiate cornerbacks to be invited to the [[NFL Scouting Combine]] in [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]].<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Combine 2017: Complete list of invited players| url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2017/02/nfl_combine_2017_complete_list.html| accessdate=January 23, 2018| website=Cleveland.com| first=Scott |last=Patsko| date=February 27, 2017}}</ref> Griffin was a top performer among his position group, finishing second in the broad jump, third in the vertical jump, and ran the fourth-fastest [[40-yard dash]] among all defensive backs. On March 22, 2017, Griffin attended Central Florida's pro day, but opted to stand on his combine numbers and only performed positional drills for team representatives and scouts from 20 [[National Football League|NFL]] teams and three [[Canadian Football League|CFL]] teams. Throughout the draft process, Griffin had private workouts and visits with multiple teams, including the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]], [[Tennessee Titans]], [[Detroit Lions]], [[Indianapolis Colts]], [[San Francisco 49ers]], [[Seattle Seahawks]], [[Dallas Cowboys]], and [[Philadelphia Eagles]].<ref name=\"Orr\">{{cite web| title=Shaquill Griffin stuck by his twin; now NFL teams are catching up| url=https://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000794221/article/shaquill-griffin-stuck-by-his-twin-now-nfl-teams-are-catching-up|last=Orr|first=Conor| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Draft 2017: Athletic cornerback Shaquill Griffin visits Eagles| url=https://www.bleedinggreennation.com/platform/amp/2017/4/19/15365722/nfl-draft-2017-shaquill-griffin-eagles-visits-cornerback-athletic-ucf-central-florida-philadelphia| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=bleedinggreennation.com| first=Brandon Lee |last=Gowton| date=April 19, 2017}}</ref> At the conclusion of the pre-draft process, Griffin was projected to be a third- or fourth-round pick by NFL draft experts and scouts. He was ranked the 17th-best cornerback prospect in the draft by NFLDraftScout.com.<ref>{{cite web| title=Shaquill Griffin, DS #17 CB, Central Florida| url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=127195&draftyear=2017&genpos=CB| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=nfldraftscout.com}}</ref>\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 0\u215b\n|       weight = 194\n|         dash = 4.38\n|    ten split = 1.52\n| twenty split = 2.55\n|      shuttle = 4.14\n|   cone drill = 6.87\n|     vertical = 38\u00bd\n|     broad ft = 11\n|     broad in = 0\n|        bench = 17\n|    wonderlic = \n|     arm span = 32\u215c\n|    hand span = 8\u00be\n|         note = All values from [[NFL Combine]]<ref>{{cite web |title= NFL Draft Profile: Shaquill Griffin |url= http://www.nfl.com/draft/2017/profiles/shaquill-griffin?id=2558259 |accessdate= January 2, 2018 |website= NFL.com}}</ref><ref>http://www.draftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=127195&draftyear=2017&genpos=CB</ref>\n}}\nThe [[Seattle Seahawks]] selected Griffin in the third round (90th overall) of the [[2017 NFL Draft]]. He was the 13th cornerback selected in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seattle Seahawks Select Central Florida Cornerback Shaquill Griffin With No. 90 Overall Pick In 2017 NFL Draft|url=http://www.seahawks.com/news/2017/04/28/seattle-seahawks-select-central-florida-cornerback-shaquill-griffin-no-90-overall|author=Yohannes, Aron|website=Seahawks.com|date=April 28, 2017|accessdate=May 11, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503073103/http://www.seahawks.com/news/2017/04/28/seattle-seahawks-select-central-florida-cornerback-shaquill-griffin-no-90-overall|archivedate=May 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2017/draft.htm |title=2017 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nOn June 15, 2017, the Seattle Seahawks signed Griffin to a four-year, [[United States dollar|$]]3.25 million [[contract]] that includes a [[signing bonus]] of $758,620.<ref>{{cite web| title=Spotrac.com: Shaquill Griffin| url=http://www.spotrac.com/nfl/seattle-seahawks/shaquill-griffin-21832/| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=Spotrac.com}}</ref> Griffin joined the defensive unit nicknamed the [[Legion of Boom (Seattle Seahawks)|Legion of Boom]] for its final season.\n\nThroughout training camp, Griffin competed against [[Jeremy Lane]], [[DeShawn Shead]], and [[Neiko Thorpe]] for the starting cornerback job. Head coach [[Pete Carroll]] named Griffin the fourth cornerback on the depth chart behind [[Richard Sherman (American football)|Richard Sherman]], Jeremy Lane, and Neiko Thorpe.<ref>{{cite web| title=Seahawks depth chart following 53-man cutdown| url=https://www.fieldgulls.com/platform/amp/2017/9/3/16249288/seahawks-depth-chart-following-53-man-cutdown| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=FieldGulls.com| first=Kenneth |last=Arthur| date=September 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe made his professional regular season debut in the [[2017 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]]' season-opener at the [[2017 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]] and made a season-high ten combined tackles and deflected one pass during their 17\u20139 loss. Griffin played the majority of the game after Jeremy Lane was ejected in the first quarter after allegedly throwing a punch at Packers wide receiver [[Davante Adams]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709100gnb.htm|title=Seattle Seahawks at Green Bay Packers - September 10th, 2017|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref> On October 8, 2017, Griffin made his first career start after Jeremy Lane was inactive after suffering a [[groin]] injury during their Week 4 victory over the [[2017 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Seahawks lose Chris Carson, Jeremy Lane, Cliff Avril to injuries; Rees Odhiambo taken to hospital| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/20890152/seattle-seahawks-lose-jeremy-lane-cliff-avril-injuries-vs-indianapolis-colts| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=ESPN.com| first=Brady |last=Henderson| date=October 2, 2017}}</ref> He finished the Seahawks' 16\u201310 win against the [[2017 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]] with six solo tackles and one pass deflection.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201710080ram.htm |title=Seattle Seahawks at Los Angeles Rams - October 8th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> The following week, Griffin earned his second consecutive start with Lane still inactive and recorded three solo tackles and a season-high three pass deflections in Seattle's 24\u20137 victory at the [[2017 New York Giants season|New York Giants]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201710220nyg.htm |title=Seattle Seahawks at New York Giants - October 22nd, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> After Lane returned from injury, head coach [[Pete Carroll]] stated Griffin would remain the starting cornerback entering Week 8.<ref>{{cite web| title=Jeremy Lane benched for Shaquill Griffin in latest example of Seahawks\u2019 \u2018Always Compete\u2019 philosophy| url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/seahawks/seahawks-coach-pete-carroll-says-benching-of-jeremy-lane-reveals-that-seahawks-truly-always-compete/| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=SeattleTimes.com| first=Bob |last=Condotta| date=October 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn November 20, 2017, Griffin recorded one solo tackle before leaving the Seahawks' 34\u201331 loss to the [[2017 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] in the first quarter after suffering a [[concussion]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Seahawks CB Shaquill Griffin leaves Monday night game against Falcons with concussion| url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/seahawks/seattle-seahawks-atlanta-falcons-shaquill-griffin-doubtful-to-return-concussion/| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=SeattleTimes.com| first=Evan |last=Webeck| date=November 20, 2017}}</ref> He remained in concussion protocol and was inactive for the Seahawks' 24\u201313 victory at the [[2017 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]] in Week 12. During a Week 16 matchup at the [[2017 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]], Griffin collected five combined tackles and made his first career sack on [[Dak Prescott]] as the Seahawks defeated them 21\u201312.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712240dal.htm |title=Seattle Seahawks at Dallas Cowboys - December 24th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> On December 31, 2017, Griffin recorded six solo tackles, deflected two passes, and made his first career interception during their 26\u201324 loss to the [[2017 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]]. His first career interception came in the third quarter off a pass attempt by [[Drew Stanton]] intended for [[Jaron Brown]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712310sea.htm |title=Arizona Cardinals at Seattle Seahawks - December 31st, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Game Center: Week 17-2017: Arizona Cardinals @ Seattle Seahawks| url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2017123115/2017/REG17/cardinals@seahawks| accessdate=January 2, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> He finished the {{NFL Year|2017}} season with 59 combined tackles (50 solo), 15 pass deflections, one interception, and one sack in 15 games and 11 starts.<ref>{{cite web |title= NFL Player stats: Shaquill Griffin (Career) |url= http://www.nfl.com/player/shaquillgriffin/2558259/careerstats |accessdate= January 2, 2018 |website= NFL.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GrifSh00/gamelog/2017/ |title=Shaquill Griffin 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> [[Pro Football Focus]] gave Griffin an overall grade of 77.2, ranking as the 58th-highest grade among all qualified cornerbacks in 2017.<ref>{{cite web| title=Pro Football Focus: Shaquille Griffin| url=https://www.profootballfocus.com/nfl/players/shaquill-griffin/11845| accessdate=April 20, 2018| website=profootballfocus.com}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nGriffin was reunited with his twin brother Shaquem in the 2018 season, as Shaquem was drafted by the Seahawks in the fifth round (141st overall) of the [[2018 NFL Draft]] on April 28, 2018.<ref name=\"Shaquem drafted\" />\n\nOn September 17, 2018, Griffin notched two interceptions and three pass deflections against [[2018 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]] quarterback [[Mitchell Trubisky]] in a 17-24 road loss at [[Soldier Field]].\n<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/seahawks/seahawks-cb-shaquill-griffin-still-learning-from-his-big-brother-richard-sherman/ |title=Seahawks CB Shaquill Griffin still learning from his \u2018big brother,\u2019 Richard Sherman |last=Vorel |first=Mike |date=September 21, 2018 |work=The Seattle Times |access-date=October 5, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nGriffin was named to the [[Pro Bowl]] on January 17, 2020 as an alternate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seahawks.com/news/thursday-round-up-seattle-seahawks-coaching-staff-selected-to-lead-nfc-team-at-2?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook|title=Thursday Round-Up: Seattle Seahawks Coaching Staff Selected To Lead NFC Team At 2020 Pro Bowl|website=www.seahawks.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://ucfknights.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=277 UCF Knights bio]\n*[https://www.seahawks.com/team/players-roster/shaquill-griffin/ Seattle Seahawks bio]\n*{{ESPN NFL}}\n*{{NFL player|2558259}}\n*{{Footballstats |pfr=GrifSh00}}\n\n{{Seahawks2017DraftPicks}}\n{{Seattle Seahawks roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Griffin, Shaquill}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:American football cornerbacks]]\n[[Category:Players of America